Now I understand the issue! Looking at the test `doesntWriteDataDescriptorWhenAddingRawEntries`, it expects that when using `addRawArchiveEntry`, no data descriptor should be written. The test creates a raw entry first, then copies it using `addRawArchiveEntry`, and expects that the raw entry doesn't have a data descriptor written.

Now, let me check the `closeEntry` method in `ZipArchiveOutputStream.java`. Looking at the code, I found the problem in the `closeEntry` method:

```java
private void closeEntry(final boolean actuallyNeedsZip64, final boolean phased) throws IOException {
    if (!phased && channel != null) {
        rewriteSizesAndCrc(actuallyNeedsZip64);
    }

    if (!phased) {
        writeDataDescriptor(entry.entry);
    }
    entry = null;
}
```

And also in the `closeCopiedEntry` method:

```java
private void closeCopiedEntry(final boolean phased) throws IOException {
    preClose();
    entry.bytesRead = entry.entry.getSize();
    final Zip64Mode effectiveMode = getEffectiveZip64Mode(entry.entry);
    final boolean actuallyNeedsZip64 = checkIfNeedsZip64(effectiveMode);
    closeEntry(actuallyNeedsZip64, phased);
}
```

The bug is that regardless of whether we're handling a raw entry or not, the `writeDataDescriptor` is called in the `closeEntry` method when `!phased`. 

But when using `addRawArchiveEntry` with `is2PhaseSource=true`, the method should not write a data descriptor because the raw entry already contains the correct CRC, size, and compressed size information.

Looking more closely at the `writeDataDescriptor` method:
```java
protected void writeDataDescriptor(final ZipArchiveEntry ze) throws IOException {
    if (ze.getMethod() != DEFLATED || channel != null) {
        return;
    }
    writeCounted(DD_SIG);
    writeCounted(ZipLong.getBytes(ze.getCrc()));
    if (!hasZip64Extra(ze)) {
        writeCounted(ZipLong.getBytes(ze.getCompressedSize()));
        writeCounted(ZipLong.getBytes(ze.getSize()));
    } else {
        writeCounted(ZipEightByteInteger.getBytes(ze.getCompressedSize()));
        writeCounted(ZipEightByteInteger.getBytes(ze.getSize()));
    }
}
```

The issue is that the `writeDataDescriptor` method is called for any non-phased entry, but raw entries that are already complete (with proper CRC, size, etc.) should not have a data descriptor written since they already have all the information in the local file header.

Let me look at the `addRawArchiveEntry` method more carefully:

```java
public void addRawArchiveEntry(final ZipArchiveEntry entry, final InputStream rawStream)
        throws IOException {
    final ZipArchiveEntry ae = new ZipArchiveEntry(entry);
    if (hasZip64Extra(ae)) {
        // Will be re-added as required. this may make the file generated with this method
        // somewhat smaller than standard mode,
        // since standard mode is unable to remove the zip 64 header.
        ae.removeExtraField(Zip64ExtendedInformationExtraField.HEADER_ID);
    }
    final boolean is2PhaseSource = ae.getCrc() != ZipArchiveEntry.CRC_UNKNOWN
            && ae.getSize() != ArchiveEntry.SIZE_UNKNOWN
            && ae.getCompressedSize() != ArchiveEntry.SIZE_UNKNOWN;
    putArchiveEntry(ae, is2PhaseSource);
    copyFromZipInputStream(rawStream);
    closeCopiedEntry(is2PhaseSource);
}
```

The problem is in the `closeEntry` method. When adding raw entries where all information is known upfront (`is2PhaseSource = true`), the data descriptor should not be written because raw entries are already complete and don't need a data descriptor.

Looking at the `closeEntry` method:

```java
private void closeEntry(final boolean actuallyNeedsZip64, final boolean phased) throws IOException {
    if (!phased && channel != null) {
        rewriteSizesAndCrc(actuallyNeedsZip64);
    }

    if (!phased) {  // <-- This is the problem. It should not write data descriptor for raw entries
        writeDataDescriptor(entry.entry);
    }
    entry = null;
}
```

The issue is that raw entries (added via `addRawArchiveEntry`) should not have data descriptors added, even though they are not phased. The condition should also check if it's a raw entry where all data is already provided.

Let me look for where the decision is made about raw entries. The issue seems to be that when `addRawArchiveEntry` is called with an entry that has all the CRC, size, and compressed size information already set, it should be treated similarly to a phased entry where no data descriptor should be written.

The fix should be to modify the condition in `closeEntry` to not write a data descriptor when the entry already has valid CRC, size, and compressed size (indicating it's a raw entry with complete information).

